\section{Conclusion}

A nonlinear model of the wooden-ball system was derived from mechanical and electrical principles and written in state-space form. The system was linearised around the equilibrium point \(x_{sp}=0.5\,\mathrm{m}\), and the Laplace transform was used to obtain a transfer function for open-loop analysis. The resulting transfer function shows that the open-loop system is unstable, since one pole lies in the right-half plane. This justifies the use of feedback control. A PID controller was selected as a practical and effective choice for achieving stability, zero steady-state error, and improved damping. Although the local linear model is useful for controller design, final validation should always be performed using the nonlinear plant and realistic disturbances.

