\section{Interview Preparation Notes}

\textbf{What are the states, input, and output?}  
The simplified states are position, velocity, and current. The input is voltage, and the output in the simplified state-space model is position.

\textbf{Why are the sensor dynamics not included in the state-space model above?}  
Because the simplified plant model is written using the mechanical and electrical states only. The sensor is then introduced later in the controller-design stage through the transfer function \(G_m(s)\).

\textbf{How accurate is the linearisation?}  
It is accurate only near the operating point. For larger deviations, the nonlinear magnetic-force and inductance terms become more significant.

\textbf{Why derive the transfer function?}  
The transfer function makes stability analysis and controller design easier by representing the input-output behaviour in the Laplace domain.

\textbf{Is the open-loop system BIBO stable?}  
No. One pole of the denominator is positive, so the open-loop system is unstable.

\textbf{Why use PID?}  
PID provides zero steady-state error and improved damping. A P controller would leave an offset, and a PI controller was considered insufficient because the derivative term is needed to improve transient behaviour.

